00:17:05,600 --> 00:17:11,280
So in 1988-89, there were all kinds 
of demonstrations in the Eastern Bloc,  

193
00:17:11,280 --> 00:17:14,080
the Soviet Union.
In the Soviet Union,  

194
00:17:14,080 --> 00:17:17,200
they're for political freedoms.
In the Eastern Bloc,  

195
00:17:17,200 --> 00:17:22,160
they're for freedom from the Soviet Union.
Gorbachev may not have gotten that detail. 

196
00:17:22,160 --> 00:17:25,280
They're all about not only 
wanting political freedoms,  

197
00:17:25,280 --> 00:17:30,880
but also they're about crumbling economies and 
how to fix their miserable standards of living. 

198
00:17:30,880 --> 00:17:34,400
Very uncharacteristically, the 
Russians didn't send tanks. 

199
00:17:34,400 --> 00:17:42,080
In fact, Gorbachev welcomed and encouraged reforms 
in the Eastern Bloc, both political and economic,  

200
00:17:42,080 --> 00:17:46,880
just as he was doing in the Soviet Union.
So his ideas of glasnost, openness,  

201
00:17:46,880 --> 00:17:58,240
and perestroika, rebuilding, resonated at home 
and abroad. These reforms began in Poland. Poland  

202
00:17:58,240 --> 00:18:07,520
had been a scene of much worker unrest many 
times, in 1956, 1970, 1976, and 1980 and 1981. 

203
00:18:07,520 --> 00:18:12,400
In 1981, this is when Solidarity, the 
workers movement, gets going and it  

204
00:18:12,400 --> 00:18:19,200
gets a national and an international reputation.
The next set of strikes are happening in 1988,  

205
00:18:19,200 --> 00:18:27,120
because in the preceding several years, the 
Polish standard of living had shrunk by over 3%. 

206
00:18:27,120 --> 00:18:34,480
The government was out of cash and wanted to raise 
basic food prices, and Poles hit the streets. 

207
00:18:34,480 --> 00:18:40,080
The government was in a panic, because it was 
worried the economy would go into free fall. 

208
00:18:40,080 --> 00:18:45,760
So the government cut a deal with Solidarity.
They said, "You call off the strikes and then  

209
00:18:45,760 --> 00:18:50,720
we'll let you into political 
talks," and Solidarity agreed. 

210
00:18:50,720 --> 00:18:55,920
There was a complicating factor on all of this.
It's called the Roman Catholic Church,  

211
00:18:55,920 --> 00:19:02,080
which is an institution of enormous credibility 
and legitimacy in Poland, which had a partiality  

212
00:19:02,080 --> 00:19:10,480
for Solidarity and it had a Polish pope.
So the roundtable discussions  

213
00:19:10,480 --> 00:19:13,760
were these political talks.
They occurred a year later in  

214
00:19:13,760 --> 00:19:19,200
February 1989, and the Soviets encouraged them.
In fact, here's one Soviet person there advising  

215
00:19:19,200 --> 00:19:24,160
the Poles: "Look, you've got to find some quick 
solutions out of your economic and political mess. 

216
00:19:24,160 --> 00:19:28,000
You're an itty-bitty country, so when you 
make mistakes, they'll be itty-bitty mistakes. 

217
00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:34,400
But if we make them, they'll be big." They 
got that one right. The Polish Communist Party  

218
00:19:34,400 --> 00:19:40,320
thought they had this one covered by the way 
they jiggered the election rules. Not quite.  

219
00:19:40,320 --> 00:19:46,720
The day they held elections is exactly 
the same day that Deng Xiaoping turned  

220
00:19:46,720 --> 00:19:53,040
the tanks on demonstrators in Beijing and you 
have the Tiananmen Massacre. Two solutions for  

221
00:19:53,040 --> 00:20:02,000
the problem. So the way the elections worked out 
in Poland is that Solidarity won every single seat  

222
00:20:02,000 --> 00:20:08,320
for which it could compete but one.
And then only three people in the  

223
00:20:08,320 --> 00:20:14,960
communist-designated seats actually won.
So who won all the rest of them? 

224
00:20:14,960 --> 00:20:21,360
The box on the ballot called "none of the above."
Yes, the Roman Catholic Church had helped  

225
00:20:21,360 --> 00:20:28,080
instruct people that that's the box you want.
With that, the legitimacy of the Communist  

226
00:20:28,080 --> 00:20:34,240
Party to rule had just been wrecked 
and we're on to democracy in Poland. 

227
00:20:34,240 --> 00:20:38,480
This democratic contagion then spread 
into East Germany four months later. 

228
00:20:38,480 --> 00:20:42,800
This is about the 40th anniversary 
of the founding of East Germany.  

229
00:20:42,800 --> 00:20:49,200
70,000 people demonstrated in Leipzig.
Within the week around like 1.4 million Germans  

230
00:20:49,200 --> 00:20:55,280
are demonstrating in over 200 demonstrations.
Typically, the East Germans would have sent tanks. 

231
00:20:55,280 --> 00:20:59,200
That was what they would have done in the past.
But would-be tank man Erich  

232
00:20:59,200 --> 00:21:04,880
Honecker was already out of a job.
His ruinous policies of living off debt since  

233
00:21:04,880 --> 00:21:12,960
he came to power in 1971 had just about wrecked 
East Germany. So he was out. Then less than two  

234
00:21:12,960 --> 00:21:19,840
weeks later, the Council of Ministers resigns.
Then on November 8th, the Politburo resigns. 

235
00:21:19,840 --> 00:21:25,280
Then on the 9th, whatever is left of that 
government is issuing new travel regulations. 

236
00:21:25,280 --> 00:21:30,640
You might wonder what travel has got 
to do with it. I'll get there. So  

237
00:21:30,640 --> 00:21:36,640
in response to a question at a news conference, 
this guy, Günter Schabowski, who was one of the  

238
00:21:36,640 --> 00:21:42,800
remaining communists helping run the show, gets 
asked a question and he doesn't know the answer.  

239
00:21:42,800 --> 00:21:46,960
So he wings it. The question is, "When do these 
travel regulations go into effect?" And he goes,  

240
00:21:46,960 --> 00:21:54,880
"Immediately." Well, crowds immediately started 
gathering at the six gates to the Berlin Wall. 

241
00:21:54,880 --> 00:21:58,880
At one of them, the border guards decided 
that discretion was the better part of valor,  

242
00:21:58,880 --> 00:22:05,200
and they opened the gate and East 
Germans poured into West Berlin. 

243
00:22:05,200 --> 00:22:11,120
Within the first week alone, over half of 
East Germany's population visited the West. 

244
00:22:11,120 --> 00:22:15,760
Within the month, 1% of the 
population emigrated to the West. 

245
00:22:16,800 --> 00:22:21,680
Like the Polish elections, this opening 
of the gate was a pivotal decision. 

246
00:22:21,680 --> 00:22:26,080
A pivotal decision, whatever it is, means 
there's no going back to the way it was. 

247
00:22:26,080 --> 00:22:29,440
Here's good old Günter going, "Gosh, we 
hadn't a clue that opening the wall was  

248
00:22:29,440 --> 00:22:39,120
the beginning of the end of East Germany." 
Okay, better luck next time. And the Russians  

249
00:22:39,120 --> 00:22:46,800
were shocked by how unpopular they were.
They were thinking they were going to get credit,  

250
00:22:46,800 --> 00:22:54,400
Gorbachev, for Eastern Europe's liberation rather 
than blame for Eastern Europe's enserfment. 

251
00:22:54,400 --> 00:22:58,560
Here you have Yuri Ryzhov, a scientist 
and parliamentarian going, "All of our  

252
00:22:58,560 --> 00:23:04,320
former satellites by compulsion cast off 
from us as fast and as far as possible." 

253
00:23:04,320 --> 00:23:10,960
And Anatoly Kovalev, who is a deputy foreign 
minister, said, "Look, we had no confidence  

254
00:23:10,960 --> 00:23:18,320
whatsoever concerning whom the East German army 
is going to shoot, the demonstrators or us. 

255
00:23:18,320 --> 00:23:23,680
And the same thing for the Polish and 
Hungarian armies." Great. With allies  

256
00:23:23,680 --> 00:23:26,800
like this, who needs enemies?
The allies kind of cover it. 

257
00:23:26,800 --> 00:23:33,920
So this argument says unrest in the empire forced 
the Soviet Union to forfeit the Cold War. Okay,  

258
00:23:33,920 --> 00:23:37,600
I got another counterargument. 
It says, "Nonsense, the real  

259
00:23:37,600 --> 00:23:43,680
problem was that the satellites were unhealthy.
That's why the whole thing fell apart. So this map  

260
00:23:43,680 --> 00:23:50,800
is 1960. You see all those tempting green places.
They're about to become independent, and they are  

261
00:23:50,800 --> 00:23:55,680
really sick of their Western European colonizers.
Enter the Soviet Union with a program to put the  

262
00:23:55,680 --> 00:24:00,960
West out of business. There were 
many takers. Fast forward to late  

263
00:24:00,960 --> 00:24:08,160
1980s. The Soviet Union is on a roll.
Small hitch, in the late 1970s there  

264
00:24:08,160 --> 00:24:14,000
was a big recession that continued into 
the 80s and tanked commodity prices. 

265
00:24:14,000 --> 00:24:22,640
For some of the newfound pals like Angola, 
South Yemen, Ethiopia, Nicaragua, it wrecked  

266
00:24:22,640 --> 00:24:27,120
their export earnings because they're exporting 
commodities and these commodity prices are down. 

267
00:24:27,760 --> 00:24:31,040
