286
00:27:18,720 --> 00:27:23,600
If you look at growth statistics for 
the Soviet Union, they're pretty good  

287
00:27:23,600 --> 00:27:30,160
post-World War II when they're rebuilding, but 
they really stagnate from the mid-70s onward. 

288
00:27:30,160 --> 00:27:37,360
For the decade preceding Gorbachev’s coming 
to power, Soviet growth stats were one to  

289
00:27:37,360 --> 00:27:44,880
two percent lower than those of the United States, 
and the compounding effects of that were enormous.  

290
00:27:44,880 --> 00:27:54,160
What's going on? Everyone's lying to each other. 
The data that Soviets are using is garbage. 

291
00:27:54,960 --> 00:28:02,400
If you're working for a subunit of an enterprise, 
you have to lie about the inventories you have,  

292
00:28:02,400 --> 00:28:07,120
saying you have less than you do, and 
then you have to lie about what you need,  

293
00:28:07,120 --> 00:28:11,920
saying you need more than you do because 
you're worried about getting enough things. 

294
00:28:11,920 --> 00:28:15,840
It's not a market system 
where the price dictates it. 

295
00:28:15,840 --> 00:28:18,240
This is all about the plan.
You've got to enter the right numbers  

296
00:28:18,240 --> 00:28:23,360
and then you get whatever inputs you get from the 
centralized plan. So everyone's lying. They're  

297
00:28:23,360 --> 00:28:28,400
aggregating all the lies. The higher up the food 
chain you aggregate these things, the worse the  

298
00:28:28,400 --> 00:28:35,913
data is, so that the Soviet government has no idea 
what the actual value of capital or labor are. 

299
00:28:35,913 --> 00:28:41,040
It has no idea what actual productivity is, and 
no one has any idea what consumer preferences are. 

300
00:28:41,040 --> 00:28:46,800
You're not using markets and prices.
The misallocation of capital and  

301
00:28:46,800 --> 00:28:53,280
labor goes unnoticed until it 
metastasizes into a catastrophe. 

302
00:28:53,280 --> 00:29:02,240
To give you a sense of these misallocations, the 
Soviet Union was rotting 20 to 40% of its crops. 

303
00:29:02,240 --> 00:29:10,160
It's using scarce hard currency for agricultural 
imports to make up for those crops, a total mess. 

304
00:29:10,720 --> 00:29:14,640
You can look at what happens to 
the economy with oil prices down. 

305
00:29:14,640 --> 00:29:20,720
We're into a spiraling mess, so that from 
when Gorbachev comes in in '85 to when it  

306
00:29:20,720 --> 00:29:29,120
hits a trough in Russia in 1998, you see this 
crashing share of world GDP by the Eastern bloc. 

307
00:29:30,480 --> 00:29:36,400
If you look at Soviet statistics on deficits, 
trade balances, debt, they're just soaring,  

308
00:29:36,400 --> 00:29:41,360
and then GNP growth goes double-digit negative. 
That's called shrinkage. It's not the normal  

309
00:29:41,360 --> 00:29:50,160
thing. Marshall Yazov, here's his take: "We simply 
lack the power of all these wealthy NATO nations. 

310
00:29:50,160 --> 00:29:57,040
We had to find an alternative to the arms race."
And here's a foreign service officer,  

311
00:29:57,040 --> 00:30:01,200
Anatoly Adamishin.
He said, "Look, our problems began  

312
00:30:01,200 --> 00:30:06,480
with the departure from isolation.
The main reasons for collapse  

313
00:30:06,480 --> 00:30:11,680
were internal, not external reasons.
The Soviet economy was literally exhausted from  

314
00:30:11,680 --> 00:30:19,120
this monstrous arms race, militarism, enemies with 
half the world." That's his take. Gorbachev told  

315
00:30:19,120 --> 00:30:25,840
the Central Committee, "Look, we're encircled not 
by invincible armies, but by superior economies." 

316
00:30:25,840 --> 00:30:31,680
He often told people, "Living this 
way any longer is impossible." 

317
00:30:31,680 --> 00:30:37,920
So you can make a powerful argument that it's 
the Soviet economy that lost the Cold War. 

318
00:30:37,920 --> 00:30:43,360
This gentleman, Alexis de Tocqueville, is 
very famous for writing a book about the  

319
00:30:43,360 --> 00:30:48,960
