Xiaoping ordered his army to do.
You just send the tanks against  

381
00:36:22,160 --> 00:36:26,560
civilian demonstrators and they 
truly crush them and it'll be over. 

382
00:36:26,560 --> 00:36:30,080
Communist Party is still in 
power in China 30 years later. 

383
00:36:30,080 --> 00:36:33,520
So there are some people who believe 
that this was a terrible mistake. 

384
00:36:33,520 --> 00:36:37,440
So this argument would be that 
timely tank deployments—TTD,  

385
00:36:37,440 --> 00:36:43,360
my contribution to military acronyms—would 
have changed the outcome of the Cold War. 

386
00:36:44,000 --> 00:36:47,920
Others would be back to the great men 
of history and sins of commission,  

387
00:36:47,920 --> 00:36:52,000
and they wouldn't be picking on Gorbachev 
but his successor Boris Yeltsin. 

388
00:36:52,800 --> 00:36:59,280
There are two big pieces of evidence when we look.
He removed Article 6 from the Soviet Constitution,  

389
00:36:59,280 --> 00:37:05,200
which guaranteed that the Communist 
Party would always monopolize power. 

390
00:37:05,200 --> 00:37:08,880
And then in addition in the following 
year, Yeltsin's the head of Russia,  

391
00:37:08,880 --> 00:37:14,720
he gets together with the heads of Ukraine and 
Belarus, and they signed the Belavezha Accords,  

392
00:37:14,720 --> 00:37:20,560
which then formally dissolved the Soviet Union.
So according to this way of thinking,  

393
00:37:21,840 --> 00:37:28,720
it's his fault. It's suicide on purpose. And 
what it does is it opens the door for multiple  

394
00:37:28,720 --> 00:37:34,560
parties and for the nationalities within 
the Soviet Empire to become independent. 

395
00:37:35,440 --> 00:37:40,160
So I've given you internal explanations. 
I've given you external explanations. Now I'm  

396
00:37:40,160 --> 00:37:47,360
going to give you some umbrella explanations.
They're based on all the preceding evidence,  

397
00:37:47,360 --> 00:37:50,560
and they come to opposite conclusions.
The first one was, well,  

398
00:37:50,560 --> 00:37:56,560
any of the above, it's inevitable.
The opposite conclusion from the same evidence is  

399
00:37:56,560 --> 00:38:02,960
that no, it took all of the above. The West barely 
won. I'm going to start with "any of the above". 

400
00:38:02,960 --> 00:38:08,480
You could argue with this many serious 
problems, it was a matter of time  

401
00:38:08,480 --> 00:38:15,440
before the Soviet Union collapsed.
It was an objectionable system for  

402
00:38:15,440 --> 00:38:21,920
precisely the reasons the West didn't like it.
It had a brutally inefficient economic system. 

403
00:38:21,920 --> 00:38:26,320
Russians who invented the thing, at the 
end of the day, didn't want it either. 

404
00:38:26,960 --> 00:38:34,800
By this way of looking at it, you have people like 
Yuri Ryzhov, a genuine rocket scientist, who says,  

405
00:38:34,800 --> 00:38:39,840
"Look, the main reason for the collapse of the 
Soviet Union is the rottenness of its system." 

406
00:38:39,840 --> 00:38:45,120
Then here's a journalist, Teimuraz Stepanov, who 
said, "Look, I think from the beginning the genes  

407
00:38:45,120 --> 00:38:50,000
of disintegration were contained in the genetics 
of this governmental political formation." 

408
00:38:50,000 --> 00:38:53,680
Don't you love the products of 
the Soviet educational system? 

409
00:38:53,680 --> 00:38:59,040
Don't ever use wording like that.
So you could argue that the Soviet Union  

410
00:38:59,040 --> 00:39:04,560
was destined to fail with this many problems.
Others would come to the opposite conclusion. 

411
00:39:04,560 --> 00:39:12,320
They would say, "No, it took every single one of 
them for the Cold War to end on Western terms." 

412
00:39:12,960 --> 00:39:18,000
Back to Anatoly Kovalev, the deputy 
foreign minister, he said, "Look,  

413
00:39:18,000 --> 00:39:24,000
all these factors merge—internal, ideological, 
economic, military—it's all of them. 

414
00:39:24,000 --> 00:39:27,120
You remove any one of them and 
you get a different outcome. 

415
00:39:27,120 --> 00:39:30,640
Maybe the Cold War ends, but it 
might end completely differently." 

416
00:39:30,640 --> 00:39:36,400
So by this line of reasoning, the West barely 
won and should feel very fortunate that it did. 

417
00:39:36,400 --> 00:39:40,400
One can take this last argument 
and say it was more than that. 

418
00:39:40,400 --> 00:39:45,440
It also took the confluence in 
office of two very talented leaders:  

419
00:39:45,440 --> 00:39:52,480
Helmut Kohl of Germany and George Bush Sr. of 
the United States, not the son who got into  

420
00:39:52,480 --> 00:39:58,880
those forever wars, but the dad who didn't.
George Bush Sr. had one of the most amazing  

421
00:39:58,880 --> 00:40:05,520
resumes of any person ever to become president 
of the United States. Just look at him. When he's  

422
00:40:05,520 --> 00:40:10,160
really young, he's a war hero in World War II.
He's a Navy pilot, a dangerous thing to do.  

423
00:40:10,160 --> 00:40:15,760
He did it. Then he comes back and he gets 
his BA at Yale and graduates with honors. 

424
00:40:15,760 --> 00:40:23,200
Then he becomes a representative for this district 
in Texas after he's already made himself a  

425
00:40:23,200 --> 00:40:29,120
millionaire in the oil business that he started.
Then he became ambassador to the UN,  

426
00:40:29,120 --> 00:40:33,680
followed by US representative to the PRC, 
before we had formal diplomatic relations. 

427
00:40:33,680 --> 00:40:38,080
So he's the guy who's setting that up.
He becomes director of the CIA, and then  

428
00:40:38,080 --> 00:40:41,440
he is Ronald Reagan's understudy 
for eight years as vice president. 

429
00:40:41,440 --> 00:40:47,760
He is incredibly fit for the job.
Helmut Kohl is equally fit for the job. 

430
00:40:47,760 --> 00:40:53,280
He is the longest-serving chancellor 
in German history since his illustrious  

431
00:40:53,280 --> 00:40:59,280
predecessor, Otto von Bismarck.
He starts out getting a PhD in  

432
00:40:59,280 --> 00:41:02,560
history and political science.
He also starts out in business,  

433
00:41:02,560 --> 00:41:07,520
but then he works for state government, initially 
as a representative, then as a governor. 

434
00:41:09,120 --> 00:41:13,360
He becomes chairman of his political 
party, the Christian Democratic Union,  

435
00:41:13,360 --> 00:41:17,280
for a quarter of a century.
Once he gets in, he decides  

436
00:41:17,280 --> 00:41:23,200
he's going to buy up East Germany one 
tourist at a time. How does that work? East  

437
00:41:23,200 --> 00:41:29,760
Germans, it turns out, really like to travel.
West Germans had always been able to travel to  

438
00:41:29,760 --> 00:41:35,280
East Germany, or they long had been able to travel 
to East Germany, but East Germans definitely could  

439
00:41:35,280 --> 00:41:40,960
not easily travel to West Germany. Why? 
Because they have a habit of staying. 

440
00:41:40,960 --> 00:41:44,880
But all of a sudden, East Germany 
eases up on the travel regulations. 

441
00:41:44,880 --> 00:41:51,520
You might ask why, and the answer would be money.
Just like the Poles, the East Germans were deep in  

442
00:41:51,520 --> 00:41:55,920
an economic mess of their own making.
Would-be tank man Erich Honecker,  

443
00:41:55,920 --> 00:42:03,680
who got the boot at the very end, well, his 
staying-in-power paradigm that he implements  

444
00:42:03,680 --> 00:42:11,280
in 1971 is that he's going to live off debt.
He needs to make certain social benefits  

445
00:42:11,280 --> 00:42:19,520
available and consumer benefits available for 
labor stability, to not have labor unrest. 

446
00:42:19,520 --> 00:42:24,000
The way he's going to do that is he's not going 
to do many domestic investments and he's going to  

447
00:42:24,000 --> 00:42:29,920
do a lot of borrowing, particularly from 
West Germany. Well, that's unsustainable  

448
00:42:29,920 --> 00:42:35,760
long-term. By the time you get to the end of 
the Cold War, if he's going to fix that and  

449
00:42:35,760 --> 00:42:41,520
even out the accounts, it would be a 30% 
decline in the East German standard of living. 

450
00:42:41,520 --> 00:42:44,400
So he really needs the pocket 
change from the tourists. 

451
00:42:44,400 --> 00:42:51,360
So what Kohl does is a brisk 
business of tourists and things. 

452
00:42:51,360 --> 00:42:56,880
What he does in return for the 
easing of travel restrictions,  

453
00:42:56,880 --> 00:43:00,320
he pays East Germany several hundred million  

454
00:43:01,040 --> 00:43:06,320
Deutschmarks extra to allow that to happen.
And then he gets the Hungarians to go along. 

455
00:43:06,320 --> 00:43:11,440
He gets the Hungarians to open up their Austrian 
border to let East Germans out that way,  

456
00:43:11,440 --> 00:43:15,440
and he gives them a half a billion 
Deutschmarks for that little favor. 

457
00:43:16,720 --> 00:43:21,120
When Kohl introduces his 10-point unification 
program—because now he's thinking he's going  

458
00:43:21,120 --> 00:43:27,120
to get both Germanys together—this is when he 
starts doling out big bucks to the Soviet Union,  

459
00:43:27,120 --> 00:43:30,880
whose economy is unraveling.
Gorbachev is going to be  

460
00:43:30,880 --> 00:43:37,360
desperate for this cash as that's happening.
So West Germany provides 100 million in food,  

461
00:43:37,360 --> 00:43:41,760
especially in meat, for the Soviet 
Union that doesn't have these things. 

462
00:43:41,760 --> 00:43:50,480
Nevertheless, the unrest just keeps on going.
The Berlin Wall, as I've told you, is breached,  

463
00:43:50,480 --> 00:43:55,600
and then you wind up with a West German 
caretaker government, and the financial  

464
00:43:55,600 --> 00:44:01,760
situation in Russia itself is unraveling.
By the time you get to January 1990, Bush and Kohl  

465
00:44:01,760 --> 00:44:06,880
get together and they decide they want to really 
fast-track German reunification. Why? Because  

466
00:44:06,880 --> 00:44:12,640
they've got to get it done before this unraveling 
crisis causes Gorbachev to fall from power. 

467
00:44:13,840 --> 00:44:20,320
So they have got a game going, the 
two of them. It's complicated. Here's  

468
00:44:20,320 --> 00:44:26,720
why. Gorbachev was dead-set against 
Germany, a united Germany, in NATO. 

469
00:44:26,720 --> 00:44:29,920
He's not really keen about a united 
Germany, let alone one in NATO. 

470
00:44:29,920 --> 00:44:33,520
The US State Department experts, the guys 
who know everything, are saying, "No,  

471
00:44:33,520 --> 00:44:40,240
you want to go slow on this unification business."
Kohl is also running a coalition government. 

472
00:44:40,240 --> 00:44:45,520
There are people in that government he cannot fire 
because they're from different political parties. 

473
00:44:45,520 --> 00:44:49,600
One of them is his foreign minister, 
this guy Genscher, who is very skeptical  

474
00:44:49,600 --> 00:44:54,640
about Germany being part of NATO.
Then it turns out, although Britain  

475
00:44:54,640 --> 00:44:58,960
had talked a good piece during the Cold War, 
it didn't actually want a unified Germany,  

476
00:44:58,960 --> 00:45:04,080
nor did France. Why? Because that unified 
Germany would eclipse them economically. 

477
00:45:04,080 --> 00:45:09,760
They didn't want that to happen.
So Kohl and Bush divide up the tasks. 

478
00:45:09,760 --> 00:45:13,360
Kohl is going to reassure the Soviet 
Union that Germany is not going to  

479
00:45:13,360 --> 00:45:17,360
be belligerent or do horrible things.
And Kohl is going to work on financial  

480
00:45:17,360 --> 00:45:21,680
unification because the Soviets are 
thinking in terms of military unification. 

481
00:45:21,680 --> 00:45:25,360
You know, where you deploy your troops. 
That determines things. Wrong instrument  

482
00:45:25,360 --> 00:45:30,000
of national power, precisely because 
the Soviets didn't understand finance. 

483
00:45:30,000 --> 00:45:35,120
That's why they're in such a mess. Whereas the 
Germans do. What they're going to do is get East  

484
00:45:35,120 --> 00:45:39,360
Germany on the West German Deutschmark, 
and at that point they will control all  

485
00:45:39,360 --> 00:45:43,280
the money and they will control decisions.
But the Russians aren't going to see that coming. 

486
00:45:43,280 --> 00:45:51,520
Meanwhile, Bush is supposed to work the alliances 
particularly with Britain and France in the West. 

487
00:45:51,520 --> 00:45:53,520
There are all sorts of 
meetings that are coming up. 

488
00:45:53,520 --> 00:45:59,520
Bush's job is to delay those meetings for 
as long as possible so German unification  

489
00:45:59,520 --> 00:46:05,440
can proceed as far as possible.
The two of them are doing a tag-team  

490
00:46:05,440 --> 00:46:11,840
diplomacy with Gorbachev that he just can't 
keep up with, given that his own home economy  

491
00:46:11,840 --> 00:46:18,160
has got these double-digit shrinkage rates. 
Here's how they go. As the trades get bigger,  

492
00:46:18,160 --> 00:46:24,560
the amount of money you pay Gorbachev gets bigger.
First of all, it's just to get a unified Germany. 

493
00:46:24,560 --> 00:46:28,320
Then it's to get a unified Germany 
with West Germany still in NATO. 

494
00:46:28,320 --> 00:46:31,680
Then it's to get a unified Germany 
with all of Germany in NATO. 

495
00:46:31,680 --> 00:46:37,680
So here's how the money goes. Gorbachev agrees 
to German unification. We are no longer paying  

496
00:46:37,680 --> 00:46:42,080
hundreds of millions of Deutschmarks.
We're paying billions of Deutschmarks,  

497
00:46:42,080 --> 00:46:48,080
five billion Deutschmarks for that one.
Then Gorbachev agrees that states can choose their  

498
00:46:48,080 --> 00:46:56,800
own alliances, i.e. whether or not to join NATO.
The US offers nine assurances, but it's also a  

499
00:46:56,800 --> 00:47:03,040
trade agreement that Gorbachev really wants.
Then the economic union goes into effect. 

500
00:47:03,040 --> 00:47:07,680
So we've now done the financial 
reunification of Germany. 

501
00:47:07,680 --> 00:47:12,160
This is when there's a London Declaration 
that's inviting Eastern European countries  

502
00:47:12,160 --> 00:47:17,600
to coordinate more closely with NATO.
In return, Gorbachev gets a promise  

503
00:47:17,600 --> 00:47:22,720
of a G7 summit meeting that's going to 
fast-track aid to him, which it will do. 

504
00:47:22,720 --> 00:47:26,960
And then Gorbachev agrees 
to German NATO membership. 

505
00:47:26,960 --> 00:47:31,920
At this point, even bigger things are happening.
Germany's going to agree to its border with  

506
00:47:31,920 --> 00:47:37,120
Poland. I'll get there and explain. Germany 
provides 15 billion in Deutschmarks,  

507
00:47:37,120 --> 00:47:41,920
including building all kinds of new apartment 
buildings for repatriated Soviet soldiers who are  

508
00:47:41,920 --> 00:47:46,080
going home. Why are you doing that? Because you 
want those soldiers focused on buying furniture,  

509
00:47:46,080 --> 00:47:52,560
not running a military coup. That's what they're 
doing. So the unification happens in mid-September  

510
00:47:52,560 --> 00:48:02,160
1990. Here's the Polish borders. At the end of 
World War II, Stalin moved Poland 200 kilometers  

511
00:48:02,160 --> 00:48:08,160
to the west, and it winds up taking a third of 
German territory by the time that's all over. 

512
00:48:08,160 --> 00:48:12,560
So the Germans don't really 
want to sign all that away. 

513
00:48:12,560 --> 00:48:17,920
In addition, as part of that, there were 12 
million German refugees who were thrown out  

514
00:48:17,920 --> 00:48:22,640
of wherever they were living to send them 
back to Germany, of whom 2 million died. 

515
00:48:22,640 --> 00:48:28,160
So this is a big deal and it's in living memory.
Germany agrees to this, that the borders are  

516
00:48:28,160 --> 00:48:36,400
done. German-Polish borders are set. Complicating 
factor: a month and a half before this unification  

517
00:48:36,400 --> 00:48:42,400
treaty is signed, Saddam Hussein decides he's 
going to invade Kuwait because he's broke. 

518
00:48:43,200 --> 00:48:48,880
He's had a long war with Iran, huge debts, many 
owed to Kuwait, which he doesn't want to pay back. 

519
00:48:48,880 --> 00:48:55,440
So if you invade them, that solves that problem.
Also, he would take over Kuwait's very rich  

520
00:48:55,440 --> 00:49:00,800
oil fields, and together that would make 
Iraq probably the swing producer of oil. 

521
00:49:00,800 --> 00:49:08,000
So he thinks that's a great idea.
Except the Cold War's over actually. 

522
00:49:08,000 --> 00:49:12,000
The Russians are more than willing 
to cooperate with the United States. 

523
00:49:12,000 --> 00:49:18,320
Gorbachev really needs more money, and he 
is willing to go along with getting Iraq out  

524
00:49:18,320 --> 00:49:24,240
of Kuwait, but not with regime change in Iraq.
Because think about it, Iraq is a very important  

525
00:49:24,240 --> 00:49:28,480
debtor state to the Soviet Union.
It owed them between $10–13 billion. 

526
00:49:28,480 --> 00:49:33,440
That's a lot of money for a broke creditor.
But Gorbachev is being extraordinarily  

527
00:49:33,440 --> 00:49:38,880
cooperative with Bush Sr.
He sends Yevgeny Primakov on  

528
00:49:38,880 --> 00:49:42,080
multiple missions to Baghdad.
The first one, Primakov  

529
00:49:42,080 --> 00:49:48,960
gets all Russian hostages out of Iraq.
Then on the second trip, he gets all Westerners  

530
00:49:48,960 --> 00:49:53,920
out, Americans included. Third trip, not so 
lucky. He's there for the coalition force bombing. 

531
00:49:53,920 --> 00:49:59,200
I don't think he liked that very much.
But imagine that bombing going on if  

532
00:49:59,200 --> 00:50:02,880
there were Western human shields 
going down with every target. 

533
00:50:02,880 --> 00:50:09,040
Russia took that card right off the table. Here's 
some of the reasoning. Sergei Tarasenko was an  

534
00:50:09,040 --> 00:50:16,640
aide to Foreign Minister Shevardnadze, and they 
understood that the United States was going to  

535
00:50:16,640 --> 00:50:25,600
do something about this invasion of Kuwait.
So the Russians thought, "It'll be better  

536
00:50:25,600 --> 00:50:31,680
if we force all of this to go through 
the UN, where Russia has a veto power." 

537
00:50:31,680 --> 00:50:36,320
He said, "Look, there was a division of roles."
It extends to China, the help that Russia  

538
00:50:36,320 --> 00:50:39,360
provided. "When the Americans 
asked us to work with the Chinese,  

539
00:50:39,360 --> 00:50:43,840
we told the Chinese, 'Think about it.
You're one of the big five with veto power. 

540
00:50:43,840 --> 00:50:48,960
Doesn't it suit your interest to funnel everything 
through the UN where you can put your foot down?'  

541
00:50:48,960 --> 00:50:56,000
And the Chinese came around to that idea."
However, the Russians had red lines. 

542
00:50:56,000 --> 00:50:59,280
Here's Anatoly Kovalev again, 
the deputy foreign minister. 

543
00:50:59,280 --> 00:51:07,360
The red line is, American troops stay out of Iraq. 
No regime change in Iraq. You do that and you will  

544
00:51:07,360 --> 00:51:12,800
tank the termination of the Cold War.
And that would be the goal. 

545
00:51:14,480 --> 00:51:18,560
Here's Kovalev saying, "I advanced the 
basic principle that we must support the  

546
00:51:18,560 --> 00:51:26,560
territorial integrity of Iraq. This was our sacred 
position. We must not permit a division of Iraq." 

547
00:51:26,560 --> 00:51:31,840
So if you wonder why the ground war 
ended after 100 hours, this is it. 

548
00:51:34,160 --> 00:51:42,800
The big thing out there is war termination of the 
Cold War. That's the big thing. Saddam Hussein is  

549
00:51:42,800 --> 00:51:52,720
a minor event over there. Sorry, but he was. 
If it had tanked Cold War termination or upset  

550
00:51:52,720 --> 00:51:57,040
the reunification of Germany, France 
and Britain might have been very happy,  

551
00:51:57,040 --> 00:52:01,680
because François Mitterrand, who is the president 
of France, and Margaret Thatcher, prime minister  

552
00:52:01,680 --> 00:52:07,680
of Britain, were against German unification.
They knew it would marginalize their own country. 

553
00:52:07,680 --> 00:52:10,160
Germany's going to be a 
bigger economy, which it is. 

554
00:52:10,160 --> 00:52:17,520
François Mitterrand eventually found solace 
in expanding the European Community to the  

555
00:52:17,520 --> 00:52:23,120
European Union when you're incorporating 
all these Eastern Bloc countries into it. 

556
00:52:23,120 --> 00:52:28,960
He plays a really important role in concluding the 
Maastricht Treaty that forms the European Union. 

557
00:52:28,960 --> 00:52:33,280
But Margaret Thatcher just plain lost.
She was just upset about the whole thing. 

558
00:52:33,280 --> 00:52:37,200
She said, "Germany will be the Japan 
of Europe and worse than Japan." 

559
00:52:37,200 --> 00:52:42,000
I guess she hadn't been to Japan lately.
She said, "The Germans will get in peace  

560
00:52:42,000 --> 00:52:48,320
what Hitler couldn't get in war."
She wanted to leave Red Army troops  

561
00:52:48,320 --> 00:52:53,040
in Germany for the duration.
Imagine if that had been the  

562
00:52:53,040 --> 00:52:59,120
case and now dealing with Putin… If he had 
troops in Germany, we would be in trouble. 

563
00:52:59,120 --> 00:53:06,560
But Bush and Kohl worked around all of them.
Bush said to Kohl at the end of it, "Look,  

564
00:53:06,560 --> 00:53:09,680
I'm not going to beat my chest 
and dance on the Berlin Wall." 

565
00:53:09,680 --> 00:53:16,720
Both of them were very careful never to humiliate 
Gorbachev about the Soviet loss of the Cold War.  

566
00:53:16,720 --> 00:53:24,720
Why? Because they knew that if they did that, he 
might fall from power sooner rather than later. 

567
00:53:24,720 --> 00:53:31,520
Also, they were afraid that if they did that, the 
hardliners would come to power much more rapidly  

568
00:53:31,520 --> 00:53:34,880
than they actually did.
It was 20 years before  

569
00:53:34,880 --> 00:53:42,640
Putin started consolidating his power.
