01:10:51,440 --> 01:10:56,080
You see them on the streets. They're already 
learning. The kids who are doing newspaper routes,  

762
01:10:56,080 --> 01:11:01,200
they're already learning about buying 
things, selling things at a very young age. 

763
01:11:01,200 --> 01:11:09,200
We just take this knowledge for granted.
It was just absent in the Soviet Union and  

764
01:11:09,200 --> 01:11:12,400
not as much absent in Eastern Europe 
that had been more connected in. 

765
01:11:13,840 --> 01:11:19,040
Before we get to the period of Russian collapse, 
let's go back to the end of the Soviet period. 

766
01:11:20,000 --> 01:11:26,160
Gorbachev starts instituting these economic 
reforms along with glasnost and perestroika. 

767
01:11:26,160 --> 01:11:32,160
But what I find mysterious is that those economic 
reforms not only fail to prevent the stagnation  

768
01:11:32,160 --> 01:11:35,520
that the Soviet Union is experiencing, 
but they in fact make things worse. 

769
01:11:36,880 --> 01:11:41,600
You would think that reform, even if it's handled 
badly, would have some sort of positive impact. 

770
01:11:41,600 --> 01:11:43,760
If you do it badly, then it'll 
have a smaller positive impact. 

771
01:11:43,760 --> 01:11:48,560
But here it just causes this huge 
hyperinflation, causes all these big problems. 

772
01:11:48,560 --> 01:11:55,680
So why did reform have this backwards impact?
There's so much that needs reforming there. 

773
01:11:55,680 --> 01:12:01,760
But part of it, I think, is because he wanted to 
do political reforms. That's what he understands.  

774
01:12:01,760 --> 01:12:06,320
As a human being, that would be the thing that 
he's very familiar with. Think about it. He's an  

775
01:12:06,320 --> 01:12:12,240
A-list member of the Communist Party to be the guy 
when they do generational change, he's the one. 

776
01:12:12,240 --> 01:12:17,440
So he's obviously very astute at that 
level, but the problem is economics. 

777
01:12:18,160 --> 01:12:24,320
He's giving away political power before 
he's fixed the economic problems. 

778
01:12:24,320 --> 01:12:30,080
China's conclusion is there is no way 
you're going to touch political power. 

779
01:12:30,080 --> 01:12:36,000
They're going to hang onto that and then deal 
with as much of the economics as they're going  

780
01:12:36,000 --> 01:12:43,680
to deal with. That’s part of it. But part of it 
is there's no tradition for all of these things. 

781
01:12:44,480 --> 01:12:47,680
Then you go, "Well, how did Russia 
get this way?" It's a very difficult  

782
01:12:47,680 --> 01:12:53,680
address. Prior to the Industrial Revolution, 
it's flat, neighbors all invade, and so you  

783
01:12:53,680 --> 01:12:59,760
needed a big army in order to defeat them.
A big army is going to want a war economy. 

784
01:12:59,760 --> 01:13:03,120
Historically, you're going to 
want to support a big land force. 

785
01:13:04,320 --> 01:13:08,320
I mean this is my take.
Others who are actually  

786
01:13:08,320 --> 01:13:12,240
experts on these various periods of Russian 
history can come up with something else. 

787
01:13:12,240 --> 01:13:16,480
But I think you're funneling, you're 
channeling your economics into that. 

788
01:13:16,480 --> 01:13:21,520
Whereas you're looking at Europe, 
particularly Britain, and it’s merchants. 

789
01:13:21,520 --> 01:13:26,640
They have a big aristocracy who are not going to 
dirty themselves with buying and selling stuff,  

790
01:13:26,640 --> 01:13:30,480
but there are a tremendous number of very 
rich merchants in Britain that are going  

791
01:13:30,480 --> 01:13:34,480
to influence government laws and things, 
which is not going to take place in Russia. 

792
01:13:34,480 --> 01:13:38,640
Then what's nice about the Navy 
for Britain is you send them away. 

793
01:13:38,640 --> 01:13:42,800
They're not going to run a coup in the capital 
because they're off on the ship somewhere. 

794
01:13:42,800 --> 01:13:45,920
And there aren't that many of 
them compared to a standing army. 

795
01:13:45,920 --> 01:13:53,680
So I suspect, I can't prove this, that this leads 
to different outcomes or contributes to them. 

796
01:13:53,680 --> 01:13:59,920
One theory I heard that is complementary to your 
theory is that Gorbachev is instituting reforms  

797
01:13:59,920 --> 01:14:03,520
because he thinks there should be decentralization 
and democratization, but he doesn't  

798
01:14:03,520 --> 01:14:09,200
fundamentally believe in the market system.
So he's delegating power to these quasi-firms. 

799
01:14:09,200 --> 01:14:12,960
At the same time, he thinks the price system 
is immoral, private property is immoral. 

800
01:14:12,960 --> 01:14:17,760
So they can't intermediate between 
themselves using real prices. 

801
01:14:17,760 --> 01:14:19,920
So then how do these firms intermediate? Well,  

802
01:14:19,920 --> 01:14:24,480
there's corruption. If you can't use actual 
prices and property to figure out who gets what  

803
01:14:24,480 --> 01:14:28,880
allocation of scarce resources, you just 
backroom deal, which makes the problem worse. 

804
01:14:28,880 --> 01:14:32,480
Well there's no legal system 
and you need a legal system. 

805
01:14:32,480 --> 01:14:36,480
Legal systems take a long time to develop.
So you're telling the Soviet Union, "Okay,  

806
01:14:36,480 --> 01:14:46,320
communism is down and now chop chop, we need 
a new legal system." It's not going to happen. 

807
01:14:47,600 --> 01:14:50,960
You were mentioning the problem that 
Eastern European countries especially had,  

808
01:14:50,960 --> 01:14:56,160
which is that they're going more and more 
into debt because they're not able to  

809
01:14:56,160 --> 01:15:03,840
produce globally competitive exports.
They have this last-ditch effort that  

810
01:15:05,200 --> 01:15:07,680
"We're going to solve our problems 
with some technological miracle. 

811
01:15:07,680 --> 01:15:12,480
We need to get even more over-leveraged.
We'll get some Western machinery or technology,  

812
01:15:12,480 --> 01:15:15,520
and then we'll be able to finally 
produce something that the world wants." 

813
01:15:16,960 --> 01:15:22,080
I'm curious up to what point 
this was a plausible hope. 

814
01:15:23,200 --> 01:15:26,480
Through the 80s and even till the 
end of the 80s, they still believed  

815
01:15:26,480 --> 01:15:30,400
that Czechoslovakia or East Germany or 
something could catch up with West Europe? 

816
01:15:30,400 --> 01:15:34,800
They're desperate. Think about 
it. If you're a communist leader,  

817
01:15:34,800 --> 01:15:38,720
how many other cards are there to play?
You're looking, "Okay, this is the  

818
01:15:38,720 --> 01:15:40,960
only card I got."
And they're doing  

819
01:15:40,960 --> 01:15:47,200
other things because of the social unrest.
They want to import food and consumer products  

820
01:15:47,200 --> 01:15:53,920
because they've been so neglected.
Then there's another piece,  

821
01:15:53,920 --> 01:16:00,080
which is VCRs, the videos.
All of a sudden, those things came around. 

822
01:16:00,080 --> 01:16:07,200
I remember being in the Soviet 
Union, the academic year of 1988-89. 

823
01:16:09,200 --> 01:16:15,760
One of my classmates had been an English 
language tutor of this person in Moscow and  

824
01:16:15,760 --> 01:16:18,720
set me up because that was the only 
way to get a good meal once a week. 

825
01:16:19,760 --> 01:16:28,000
For a meal, I would talk English for an hour.
What that family wanted more than  

826
01:16:28,000 --> 01:16:34,240
anything else was a VCR player.
You could have hard currency and  

827
01:16:34,240 --> 01:16:40,320
buy it at the diplomatic store.
So I basically got them a VCR by  

828
01:16:40,320 --> 01:16:43,840
going to the diplomatic thing with 
my very limited foreign currency. 

829
01:16:43,840 --> 01:16:49,520
I bought an overpriced VCR for them and got 
all kinds of meals for the rest of the year. 

830
01:16:49,520 --> 01:16:54,000
But it meant that they could all 
of a sudden get Western movies. 

831
01:16:55,280 --> 01:17:01,280
There are things in movies where there'll 
be a picture of a fugitive running by  

832
01:17:02,000 --> 01:17:10,480
the fruit section of the Berkeley Bowl.
The Russians would gasp like, "Oh." It's  

833
01:17:10,480 --> 01:17:17,520
unbelievable. I think that Raisa Gorbachev, 
Gorbachev's wife, when she came and visited,  

834
01:17:17,520 --> 01:17:23,120
she must have realized that a welfare mother on 
food stamps had better buying power than she did  

835
01:17:23,120 --> 01:17:28,400
by just being able to have access to Walmart.
I think the elites, as they're traveling… I  

836
01:17:28,400 --> 01:17:32,000
have no statistical data on this, 
but as you travel, it's like I'm  

837
01:17:32,000 --> 01:17:40,320
comparing me getting sour cream in a jar.
That was the other thing, counting up all  

838
01:17:40,320 --> 01:17:47,440
the things in a Soviet supermarket.
The total was something like 77  

839
01:17:47,440 --> 01:17:52,640
items total in this supermarket.
I don't think that compares favorably  

840
01:17:52,640 --> 01:17:59,040
to a candy rack as you leave a 7-Eleven.
And when you went by the meat section,  

841
01:17:59,040 --> 01:18:06,160
the smell just about knocked you out, rotten 
meat. It was really disgusting. I got really  

842
01:18:06,160 --> 01:18:09,360
good at making borscht.
Go to the peasant market,  

843
01:18:09,360 --> 01:18:15,040
pay hard currency for bones, because I couldn't 
afford any meat, but I could afford the bones. 

844
01:18:15,040 --> 01:18:20,080
Then I would buy… The Russians produce 
really good sugar beets so I got beets. 

845
01:18:20,080 --> 01:18:24,400
Then you're starting to get rotten apples over 
the winter, but they at least come from Hungary. 

846
01:18:24,400 --> 01:18:27,920
Russians didn't even produce apples 
in those days, but Hungarians did. 

847
01:18:27,920 --> 01:18:32,480
The Romanians provided the canned tomatoes, 
and I could do a credible borscht. 

848
01:18:32,480 --> 01:18:37,920
But you're talking about Moscow, 
the center of everything. 

849
01:18:39,040 --> 01:18:44,640
I remember buying potatoes at the market 
and the rotten spots felt gelatinous. 

850
01:18:44,640 --> 01:18:47,760
So you'd have to cut those out.
And then you're wondering how many  

851
01:18:47,760 --> 01:18:51,200
nutrients are in the rest of that potato.
It was a really gross year. 

852
01:18:52,240 --> 01:18:59,760
I remember going to the candy store and I 
would buy caramel from Poland or somewhere. 

853
01:18:59,760 --> 01:19:03,440
It was like a food item 
because it was actually edible. 

854
01:19:03,440 --> 01:19:05,920
At this point, I bet you were wondering 
why you didn't write a biography of  

855
01:19:05,920 --> 01:19:10,960
Napoleon so you could just visit Paris instead.
My brother's comment is, "You're studying Russia  

856
01:19:10,960 --> 01:19:18,400
and China, two countries in the breakdown lane."
By the way, the point about the grocery stores  

857
01:19:18,400 --> 01:19:25,760
having 74 items is interesting in two ways.
One, central control works much better if you have  

858
01:19:25,760 --> 01:19:30,000
a much smaller amount of items to optimize over.
So if things are standardized,  

859
01:19:30,000 --> 01:19:33,520
it can work much better.
And second, to your point about GDP being  

860
01:19:33,520 --> 01:19:37,440
hard to compare between the Soviets and the United 
States, how do you compare a rotten tomato or a  

861
01:19:37,440 --> 01:19:43,040
rotten potato to the Idaho ones that you can get?
They would have compared it by pound. 

862
01:19:43,040 --> 01:19:44,240
Exactly.
Yeah. 

863
01:19:44,240 --> 01:19:48,640
You said you were there in '88 and '89.
So this is before the Berlin Wall has fallen. 

864
01:19:48,640 --> 01:19:54,480
I was watching the Tiananmen 
demonstrations on Soviet TV. 

865
01:19:54,480 --> 01:19:59,520
The only reason you got that TV coverage 
is because Gorbachev was in Beijing. 

866
01:19:59,520 --> 01:20:03,360
So all the press was there.
That's why you have the coverage. 

867
01:20:03,360 --> 01:20:08,880
And they stayed on because the students were 
demonstrating and the Chinese closed society  

868
01:20:08,880 --> 01:20:14,000
wasn’t aware of the power of television.
Guys, they're going to film you doing all  

869
01:20:14,000 --> 01:20:22,160
of this stuff and they will get the film out.
In '88, was the mood… Obviously things are going  

870
01:20:22,160 --> 01:20:27,680
terribly, but did people realize that they're 
only two years away, or three years away from the  

871
01:20:27,680 --> 01:20:32,400
complete dissolution of the Soviet Union?
No. Maybe the end of the Soviet Union,  

872
01:20:32,400 --> 01:20:38,640
but there was such optimism of thinking we're 
finally going to be a full-up democratic country. 

873
01:20:38,640 --> 01:20:46,400
It's going to be wonderful, with no sense of the 
work schedules that go into a capitalist economy. 

874
01:20:46,400 --> 01:20:52,240
To create the wealth in this country, a lot of 
people are working far more than 40 hours a week,  

875
01:20:52,880 --> 01:20:57,040
particularly as they're getting 
started, working enormous hours. 

876
01:20:57,840 --> 01:21:01,760
That was not something that 
was in most people's minds. 

877
01:21:01,760 --> 01:21:08,000
Sure, the kids who became the ballerinas in 
the Bolshoi are working long hours to do that. 

878
01:21:08,000 --> 01:21:15,040
But as an economy as a whole, they didn't 
understand the source of wealth and had no  

879
01:21:15,040 --> 01:21:20,880
inkling of all the things that are missing, 
not least of which is that no one's got the  

880
01:21:20,880 --> 01:21:27,520
right education. Great, you got Marx 
memorized. That does you zero good. 

881
01:21:27,520 --> 01:21:31,680
So around this time is when people are finally 
learning about what actually happened during the  

882
01:21:31,680 --> 01:21:33,360
Stalinist period.
Oh, yeah. 

883
01:21:33,360 --> 01:21:36,800
So people are optimistic that 
we can have a changing of the  

884
01:21:36,800 --> 01:21:39,040
guard and maybe things will improve.
But at the same time, they're learning  

885
01:21:39,040 --> 01:21:45,200
about how terrible their history actually was.
Between these two things… Also at some point  

886
01:21:45,200 --> 01:21:48,800
they must realize through the 90s that 
things actually aren't improving. In fact,  

887
01:21:48,800 --> 01:21:54,080
they're getting worse. So what is the 
inflection point at which the mood is just... 

888
01:21:54,080 --> 01:21:59,440
I don't know, because I wasn't living there.
I was thinking that there would be impending  

889
01:21:59,440 --> 01:22:05,600
problems as a Chicken Little American.
The sky is falling, the sky is falling. 

890
01:22:05,600 --> 01:22:10,080
Americans always think disaster is coming.
I sort of fit in that crowd. 

891
01:22:10,080 --> 01:22:14,000
But I think there was a lot of 
optimism and exuberance thinking,  

892
01:22:14,000 --> 01:22:17,600
"We have the freedom to really understand 
our history and what's happening." 

893
01:22:17,600 --> 01:22:26,640
This is for educated people, people with college 
degrees in Moscow and St. Petersburg. Now what's  

894
01:22:26,640 --> 01:22:31,440
going on in the rest of the country is 
undoubtedly a different story because  

895
01:22:32,560 --> 01:22:40,320
as bad as living in Moscow was, living in the 
countryside was going back in time far further. 

896
01:22:40,320 --> 01:22:47,760
So those people weren't living well at all.
And it's going to get really bad for them. 

897
01:22:47,760 --> 01:22:50,720
Okay, so people are learning about 
these things for the first time. 

898
01:22:50,720 --> 01:22:55,440
Is the sense that they kind of suspected? I 
mean, people have family. They must have known,  

899
01:22:55,440 --> 01:23:02,800
"My uncle was off in this little mining 
town that he was forced to go to for a  

900
01:23:02,800 --> 01:23:07,760
decade right after World War II."
Were they totally shocked or was  

901
01:23:07,760 --> 01:23:11,120
there some sense that things were pretty bad 
and now we're just learning the extent of it? 

902
01:23:11,120 --> 01:23:15,120
I think there was an understanding it was 
terrible, but I think there's this exuberance  

903
01:23:15,120 --> 01:23:21,120
of thinking it's going to get much better.
Then the disappointment is equally extreme. 

904
01:23:21,120 --> 01:23:29,040
And then there was this feeling that the West 
owes us because you're all really rich and  

905
01:23:29,040 --> 01:23:33,600
you now owe us to fix everything.
The counterargument to that is,  

906
01:23:33,600 --> 01:23:38,400
"No you are an enormous migraine.
You set back all of these countries  

907
01:23:38,400 --> 01:23:45,440
across the globe in time with this nonfunctioning 
communist model that you peddled around there. 

908
01:23:45,440 --> 01:23:52,640
And now you want extra aid."
The problem was that we wanted to do some of the  

909
01:23:52,640 --> 01:23:57,280
aid, but they're not going to be receptive to it.
That was another conclusion with the Bush  

910
01:23:57,280 --> 01:24:01,360
administration, that if we dumped a lot of money 
in it, it would just go straight into corruption. 

911
01:24:02,080 --> 01:24:07,360
You need a legal structure in order to place 
money, and they just plain didn't have it. 

912
01:24:07,360 --> 01:24:10,160
That was another thing that was 
worrying the Bush administration. 

913
01:24:10,160 --> 01:24:15,120
There's nowhere to put the money.
Speaking of these different countries that  

914
01:24:15,120 --> 01:24:20,400
the Soviets and the United States were competing 
for during the Cold War, you had this presentation  

915
01:24:20,400 --> 01:24:26,240
where you say Reagan alone didn't do this.
But I wonder if the broader lesson is that  

916
01:24:27,200 --> 01:24:31,440
nothing any US president did in terms of 
foreign policy… That was all a sideshow,  

917
01:24:31,440 --> 01:24:36,720
this tête-à-tête competition for different Third 
World countries: "We're going to get Brazil, we're  

918
01:24:36,720 --> 01:24:43,760
going to get Vietnam, we're going to get Algeria."
That just seems much less significant than the  

919
01:24:43,760 --> 01:24:48,000
fact that liberal capitalism was more 
appealing and out-produced communism. 

920
01:24:48,000 --> 01:24:51,920
So even if some country, even if Brazil 
goes communist, this is not going to change  

921
01:24:53,600 --> 01:24:58,560
the fundamental playing board here.
If you do not protect the liberal economies  

922
01:24:58,560 --> 01:25:06,240
of Europe, you're not going to have anywhere to 
play the liberal economic game, and also Japan. 

923
01:25:06,240 --> 01:25:09,840
One of the reasons you feel that liberal 
economies work is you've got economic  

924
01:25:09,840 --> 01:25:15,200
miracles going on in Japan, Korea, Taiwan, 
Singapore, and Hong Kong back in the day. 

925
01:25:15,200 --> 01:25:20,400
So if you abandon those places...
Also in the Cold War, there was a  

926
01:25:20,400 --> 01:25:26,080
tremendous amount of economic growth across 
the world, particularly in the Third World.  

927
01:25:26,080 --> 01:25:32,240
Why? Because in the past, if there's a civil 
war, whoever's losing either comes to us or  

928
01:25:32,240 --> 01:25:37,120
comes to the Russians and says, "Help us."
So whoever it is helps, and then the other  

929
01:25:37,120 --> 01:25:42,320
side feels obliged to help, and then you're 
just destroying wealth ever more rapidly. 

930
01:25:43,440 --> 01:25:46,960
The Cold War was anything 
but cold in the Third World. 

931
01:25:46,960 --> 01:25:50,080
Tens of millions of people 
died in these conflicts. 

932
01:25:50,080 --> 01:25:54,560
So when you end that, all of a sudden 
they can start compounding growth. 

933
01:25:54,560 --> 01:26:00,400
So there is a problem with not 
countering someone who's going  

934
01:26:00,400 --> 01:26:03,600
to impose communist systems all over the place. 

935
01:26:03,600 --> 01:26:07,920
Communist systems are really 
good at putting dictators into  

936
01:26:07,920 --> 01:26:12,960
power in a civil war situation. It's very 
effective. That's how Mao gets into power. 

937
01:26:13,520 --> 01:26:16,640
The problem is, then they win 
the civil war, they're in power,  

938
01:26:16,640 --> 01:26:22,000
they annihilate the opposition, but then 
it produces compounding poverty thereafter. 

939
01:26:22,000 --> 01:26:24,560
So there is this conundrum, and I 
genuinely don't know the answer to this. 

940
01:26:26,080 --> 01:26:31,360
In order to beat off these communist factions 
and guerrillas, we often through the Cold War  

941
01:26:31,360 --> 01:26:37,520
had to support other dictators.
Probably in many cases they were  

942
01:26:37,520 --> 01:26:40,640
better than the communist alternative.
It's just very hard to beat Pol Pot  

943
01:26:40,640 --> 01:26:49,520
and Mao in terms of how terrible you can be.
But obviously this was in its own way problematic. 

944
01:26:49,520 --> 01:26:53,680
Even if we didn't have to support 
dictators, we had to alienate countries. 

945
01:26:53,680 --> 01:26:57,760
You had this previous lecture that you gave 
on the Indo-Pakistani chapter in history where  

946
01:26:57,760 --> 01:27:04,000
we had to alienate India in order to fend off 
against the Soviet Union in this little episode. 

947
01:27:04,720 --> 01:27:08,800
I don't know what the solution to this is.
If you think that this theater mattered less, then  

948
01:27:08,800 --> 01:27:14,320
you could say we should have just kept our hands 
clean of these different Third World countries. 

949
01:27:14,320 --> 01:27:17,520
But to your point, if you want to be able to 
show that these countries are going to experience  

950
01:27:17,520 --> 01:27:21,360
growth under capitalism, then you want them 
to not be under the subjugation of communists. 

951
01:27:21,360 --> 01:27:24,800
But then you have to support 
